<subSubSection id="72EE6553FF87FFDAD691D399FB82F879" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="3A4B36D8FF87FFDAD691D399FB82F879" blockId="76.[151,1437,966,2037]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="0880EACAFF87FFDAD691D399FEECF85C" bold="true" box="[199,322,1974,2000]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="FDF44D5BFF87FFDAD432D398FD57F85D" authorityName="Chen &amp; Pu" authorityYear="1980" box="[612,761,1975,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Adiscus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occipitalis">
<emphasis id="0880EACAFF87FFDAD432D398FD57F85D" box="[612,761,1975,2001]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">A. occipitalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the latter has fine and dense punctures on pronotum, its elytra with epipleura hardly visible in lateral view, and venter is yellowish brown.
</paragraph>
